Getting Started with Dune Analytics

7 steps

Regardless of your level of experience in the web 3 space, you may or may not be familiar with Dune and its associated functionalities.

In this tutorial, we will delve deeper into Dune Analytics, exploring its advantages and gaining a better understanding of its interface. Additionally, we will offer a detailed, step-by-step walkthrough on how to navigate and make the most of the Dune Analytics interface.

Lets get started!
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

There are no pre-requisites!

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Describe Dune and its benefits
  • Describe Dune key components and its essential components
  • Navigate through the Dune interface

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: What is Dune Analytics?

    Dune is an exceptional and cost-free tool for analyzing blockchain data, providing users with the capability to access nearly real-time data from the blockchain through a public database. With the convenience of querying this data directly on their website using SQL, Dune has quickly emerged as a rapidly expanding platform of choice among developers. Its popularity stems from the vast amount of blockchain data accessible online, enabling developers to derive valuable insights from trading platforms and prominent crypto exchanges.

    Dune simplifies the process of incorporating blockchain data into their database by decoding it, eliminating the need for users to navigate bytecode communication (exchange of low-level instructions between different components or systems within a blockchain network) themselves. Dunes data analytics tools focus on popular blockchains like Ethereum, Polygon, and BSC. But users can use these tools to look at any network that is not natively supported by Dune. Users can conveniently explore datasets, specific smart contracts, events, or calls using Dune's dataset explorer!

    Although we did mention that making queries on Dune is primarily done through SQL syntax, there are some subtle differences you should take note of in this docs (but shouldn't matter that much).

    We will cover more query related content in the upcoming quests.

  • Step 2: Benefits of Dune Analytics

    The popularity of Dune Analytics primarily derives from its flexibility and extensibility. This unique capability empowers users to design customized dashboards and analytic tools that concentrate on specific metrics related to popular blockchain networks. In just a moment, we will present some of these impressive features to you.

    But in a quick summary, these are some of the features that makes Dune a popular choice amongst many Web3 developers:

    User-Friendly Interface

    Querying data on Dune SQL is relatively fast as compared to other platforms and has much better ergonomics (interface that is designed to be more comfortable and efficient for people to use).

    The thoughtful team at Dune SQL has also built a tool to automatically help make query changes for you, without the need for you to fully translate your own code into their syntax. This means that as long as you can code in SQL, transition to Dune SQL is as easy as abc, as you will see in following quests.

    Active Dune Community

    Dune SQL has interactive dashboards featuring queries done by numerous other developers, meaning everything you have created can be viewed / forked by anybody.

    This allows other developers (such as yourself) to build off existing queries and combine queries to create more insightful queries!

    This also gives inspiration and allows devs to build on existing work to deliver new insights by studying public dashboards. This also means that your findings can help somebody else, acting as a good portfolio for your data analytics skills.

    Developer Centric Tools

    Given its vast blockchain datasets, there are endless possibilities and investigations to be conducted, so as to gain more insights and findings from the process with the new Dune Engine V2. They provide specific table columns for us to investigate further.

    Prior to dune, other tools for crypto / market watch include Messari and Nansen, which are data and insights offered by third parties. Now with dune, developers have the autonomy to conduct their own analysis specifically for details or insights they want, and no longer need to be as dependent on these third parties.

    Most importantly, developers can just focus on building meaningful queries without the need to maintain data engineering pipelines to write a simple query!

    Are you convinced by the power of Dune analytics? If you do, let's take a deeper dive into how we can effectively utilize it to access and analyze blockchain data.

  • Step 3: Account Creation

    Of course, before we begin, it's important to have a Dune account before we can begin conducting any analysis. Head over here and click sign up. Then proceed to fill in your particulars and create your account!

    Note that if you have successfully set up your account, your dashboard should look like the above image, with your username visible at the top.

    In a quick overview, the Dune interface consists of the following components namely dashboards, queries, wizards and teams. We will now proceed to introduce each feature in the following steps!

  • Step 4: User Dashboard

    Let's start by exploring the user dashboard, which forms the foundation of a vibrant community as mentioned in step 2. Before we begin writing our own queries, it's beneficial to examine the code and visualizations created by other developers. This allows us to learn from their techniques and understand how they create their very own insightful analysis.

    In the above image, we can see that the highlighted section displays a list of user dashboards, which showcases the dashboards created by other users. Dashboards can be ranked according to 3 options: Favorites, Trending and New. This gives users a filter for visualizations that are ranked according to their preference. By default, it will be ranked by Trending, which are dashboards that are currently popular and frequently visited by other devs. Favorites on the other hand filters and ranks dashboards by the number of stars given, while New simply showcases the latest dashboards created in the past few hours.

    You have the liberty too to search for specific dashboards, or filter for dashboards creations from the time range buttons.

    By clicking on the user created Dashboards, in my case Best GMX Traders that appeared on the top of my feed as the top trending dashboard (may be different for yours by the time you are attempting this), it will proceed to show you an overview of the user-created dashboard consisting of different visualizations and numerical insights as shown below.

    The above image shows numerical insights, while the image below shows an example of a visualization within the same dashboard.

    Creating our very own dashboard will be something that we will explore in the future, which looks exactly like this! As you can see, this dashboard will update continuously with the influx of new blockchain data that is coming in, helping third party devs / analysts study the trend of trades. Pretty neat right? Lets move on to the other important feature, queries, in the next step.

  • Step 5: Queries

    A dashboard in essence is just a space containing different visualizations and insights that are produced by queries. To get a better understanding of queries, simply click on any one of the headers to open up the queries tab.

    Upon clicking on the headers, you should see the queries page come up. (As shown in the image below)

    Dont worry if some of the code seems really cryptic, like the one featured above. The main purpose isnt to scare you off, but rather to introduce the query interface. This is where all the SQL coding is done, the backend that is working to keep the visualizations and insights running in the on the dashboards. 

    Looking at the top right side, forking will be an important feature: giving you the ability to build on top of the work of other devs. By clicking on the fork button, the browser refreshes into a new query mode that looks slightly different.

    Here, you have more freedom and flexibility to edit and alter the code by the original dev to discover new findings, putting your SQL skills that you have learnt in the previous campaign into good use!

    Suppose that you want to incorporate new data into the existing data that the dev is using, then we would need a completely new set of data that can be easily queried by the dataset explorer. Lets now shift our focus to the dataset explorer by the side.

    Here is a quick list of breakdown of the important features of the dataset explorer:

    V2 Dune SQL

    The default option for making quick queries and more user-friendly in general. Developers at dune are building tools to make it easier to make queries in contrast to the older datasets. You can read more about it here.

    Searchbar

    Self-explanatory -> simply query for the databases you have in mind before performing necessary queries

    Essentials

    Popular datasets relating to decentralized exchange and nft data

    Encompasses ample data for analysis touching on common analysis pertaining to the web3 domain

    Raw

    Raw data consisting of popular cryptocurrencies such as Ethereum, arbitrum and avalanche.

    Provides different datasets from creation traces, transactions and gas prices which we will cover more in detail next.

    In case youre wondering, other datasets under decoded projects, spells and community are less important at this stage, so we wont be covering them. But of course, feel free to explore in your own time!

  • Step 6: Wizards and Teams

    On Dune's platform, those who can skillfully transform SQL code into captivating insights and visualizations are affectionately referred to as "Wizards." It's a playful and unique way that Dune labels developers who demonstrate exceptional expertise in crafting compelling analyses and visuals.

    Wizards excel at crafting spells, and the "Spellbook tables" serve as "Abstraction and Aggregation Tables for Blockchain Data." These tables are maintained collaboratively by Dune and the community, enabling them to establish a standardized approach for transforming data into meaningful abstraction layers. Complementing Web3 data, which provides a foundational layer of raw data structured as transactions and logs, these spells allow the creation of custom and abstracted data sets. By aggregating and organizing data from various sources, they simplify the querying process through data engineering pipelines significantly.

    For instance, conventional approaches of querying data include scraping through contracts and writing multiple queries to navigate and query desired columns. With spells, all the hassle is done and the rest of the community could skip all the noise to get straight to building meaningful queries! An example would be nft.trades, which makes it easy to explore and analyze all NFT marketplace data without having to aggregate each NFT marketplace.

    When you return to the user dashboard, you'll find the "Wizard" tab, which showcases a leaderboard of developers ranked by the total number of favorites they've earned. The top-ranking wizards are those who have made substantial contributions to the community, demonstrating their significant impact and involvement on the platform.

    Feel free to utilize the search bar on the side if you wish to find specific Wizards and keep track of their work. By clicking on their usernames, you can explore the various Dashboards they have collaborated on over the past year, along with their personal profiles. This feature is truly remarkable and can serve as a valuable personal portfolio, especially for aspiring professional web3 developers or data analysts. It allows users like yourself to showcase their expertise and contributions within the Dune Analytics community!

    Lastly, within Dune Analytics, teams display the collaborative efforts of Wizards who come together to build dashboards. If you enjoy working as part of a team, you have the option to join teams based on invitation only. Alternatively, if you're up for the challenge, you can create your own team. However, it's essential to do so only after you have thoroughly mastered the basics of Dune Analytics, which you will undoubtedly achieve by the end of this module!
